as also been recorded since medieval times in Ireland.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish names."],"variants":[{"name":"Parkman","meanings":["English:","occupational name from Middle English <i>park</i> ‘enclosure, game preserve, park’ (Old French <i>parc</i>) + <i>man</i>, sometimes for one living at or near such a place but probably more often denoting someone employed to look after after deer and other game in a hunting park; compare   Parker  .","occupational name denoting the servant (Middle English <i>man</i>) of someone called <i>Park</i> (see   Park   2)."]},{"name":"Parkerson","meanings":["English: from the occupational name   Parker   + patronymic <i>-son</i>."]},{"name":"Parkey","meanings":["English (Cheshire and Lancashire): dialect pronunciation of   Parker  . <i>Parker</i> has a long history in Macclesfield, Manchester, and Bridgnorth."]},{"name":"Park","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Young, Sang, Sung, Yong, Jung, Jong, Chan, Jae, Jin, Kwang, Kyung, Myung, Chong, Chang, Chung, Byung, Min, Moon, Chul, Hae, Jeong, Dae, Seong, Myong.","English and Scottish: from Middle English and Older Scots <i>parc</i>, <i>parke</i>, <i>perk</i> ‘park, enclosure’ (Old French <i>parc</i>), often referring to the grounds of a manor house or a deer park where the lord hunted. The name was probably synonymous with   Parker  , denoting an officer who looked after a park for the lord of the manor.","English and Scottish: from a medieval pet form of the personal name   Peter  . Compare   Parkin  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":6,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":31,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":44,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When William Parker was born in 1284, in England, his father, John Parker, was 29 and his mother, Margaret de Harley, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1284–":"1284–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1316–Female":"1316–Surnud","1256–Male":"1256–Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"1284–":"1284–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1316–Female":"1316–Kuollut","1256–Male":"1256–Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","1256":"1256","1284":"1284","1260":"1260","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290